President Obama met with South Korean President Lee Myung-bak to discuss the global economic crisis, North Korea, and other areas of cooperation. They agreed to work together to stimulate their economies and reform the international regulatory system. They emphasized the importance of avoiding protectionism and economic nationalism. President Obama reaffirmed his commitment to the U.S.-ROK alliance and pledged continued cooperation to strengthen it. They also discussed the U.S.-Korea Free Trade Agreement and the potential benefits it could bring to both countries. The leaders shared a vision for broadening and modernizing the Alliance and discussed increasing regional and global cooperation. They promised to continue working together to peacefully eliminate North Korea's nuclear programs and urged North Korea to abide by U.N. Security Council resolutions. President Obama appreciated South Korea's contributions in promoting stability in the Afghanistan-Pakistan region and they pledged to cooperate on global challenges such as climate change and clean energy technologies.